  "articleSummary": "**Summary:**  \nThe article argues that using a fixed‑choice “Priority” dropdown (e.g., P1‑P4) in issue trackers quickly becomes a trap as organizations grow, leading to endless hacks like “P0”, “P00”, and ever‑higher numeric values. It frames this problem with a startup‑story metaphor and a recurring “z‑index war” analogy, warning that an unbounded priority field inflates like UI layering and eventually loses meaning. The author recommends abandoning the single‑select model in favor of neutral numeric baselines, composite scores, or dynamic methods such as MoSCoW or the Kano model, and stresses that most backlog items will never be completed, so archiving and periodic re‑evaluation are essential. The tone is a mix of informal rant and practical analysis aimed at engineers, product managers, and Jira administrators who design or maintain ticket‑triage systems.",
